{
  "doc_id": "6433",
  "text": "Biomol Ther 23(5), 421-427 (2015) Imperatorin, belonging to a group of furanocoumarins and found in Angelicae Dahuricae Radix, is known to have various biological functions, including anti-inflammatory activity. It showed inhibitory activity on the LPS-induced NO and PGE2 production by suppressing elevated iNOS and COX-2 protein expression as well as the release of pro-inflammatory cytokines through the inactivation of MAPKs and NF-κB in RAW 264.7 cells [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Huang et al., 2012; [CITATION_3] . In addition, imperatorin reduced the development of carrageenan-induced paw edema in vivo (Huang et al., 2012) . Furthermore, imperatorin exerted inhibitory effects in an allergic rhinitis model and in an in vitro assay by regulating caspase-1 activity [CITATION_4] .",
